statements.statement: Supervisor guiding my understanding and not giving answers.
When needed, supervisor engaging in positive confrontation.
Supervisor creating a space of positivity.
The sense that supervisor would report anything I say to the professor so it was easier to just not say anything at all.
Supervisor pointing out statements I made and encouraging me to think about the statement.
Supervisor not staying within the confines of an appropriate supervisor-supervisee relationship.
The feeling of community in the supervision.
Supervisor providing feedback in a confusing and unclear manner even after I expressed that I am open to specific and straightforward feedback.
Supervisor matching my energy in a productive way whether it was laughing at times or being really serious at other times.

My eagerness to learn and grow within the supervision process.

The structured environment supervisor required during supervision along with expectations with assignments.
Supervisor’s willingness to listen and offer advice.
Supervisor’s understanding on we don't always need a strict agenda to talk through.
Both of us being open to feedback.
The trust between me and supervisor.
Supervisor providing psychoeducation via PowerPoint concerning certain topics (ACT, CBT, etc.).
Supervisor’s lack of knowledge concerning authenticity.
Supervisor’s effort in holding me accountable in a way that made me more productive.
Supervisor asking my input about my session.
Supervisor addressing what is showing up for me in sessions.
The feedback I received from supervisor that was instrumental in helping me gauging how I was engaging with clients for the first time.
Supervisor’s self-disclosure to remind me they were once where I was.
Supervisor genuinely getting to know who I am as a person.
Supervisor’s inability to understand perspectives outside of their own.
Supervisor not allowing me to practice my own flavor of therapy.
